column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. parked at Clean Harbor’s in transit storage location in Bristol, CT for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities of hazardous waste for continuing transportation to the intended waste management facility. Upon routine inspection, it was discovered that approximately one gallon of material escaped from the container. Response personnel donning personal protective equipment placed the leaking container into a suitable salvage drum along with all clean-up debris from the van trailer. The container was secured and was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility. All required local and state reports were made that included verbal reports to the Connecticut Department of Environmental Protection and local Fire Department.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. The driver, however, was re-instructed to conduct a thorough inspection of each container before acceptance and if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take appropriate action to either place the container into a suitable salvage drum or re containerize before transportation is initiated.

During a routine yard check at the ten day storage yard of the intended waste disposal facility, a rolloff box was noticed to be leaking a small amount of liquid.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the spill with a suitable absorbant material, which was then placed back into the box.
column169: The shipper was notified that no free liquids must be able to separate from the solid material during the rigors of transportation.  The box was not leaking nor were there any visible liquids at the time of pickup or acceptance into the ten day yard.

column168: Upon tank car arrival on track at the TRANSFLO location and during the tank car inspection, while the operator was attempting to loosen the bell cap on the bottom of the railcar, Petroleum Crude Oil started leaking out of the product valve into the bell cap during the loosening of the cap.  The bell cap was immediately tightened.  Approximately 1 quart of product hit the drip pan that was under the tank car.  Petroleum Crude Oil did not start leaking until the operator started to loosen the cap for removal.  There was no evidence of any residue product on the bell cap prior to the inspection.  The bottom valve will be repaired after the tank car is unloaded from the top of the tank car instead of the bottom product valve.
column169: The Shipper was notified of the leakage around the bottom bell cap.  The tank car will be repaired before releasing for transit.  The Shipper will contact the repair company.

column168: DHL Express Dangerous Goods Manager, Shawn Pandorf, was contacted by the FAA to advise a potential hidden dangerous goods shipment was moving through the DHL network. column168: After arrival and deramping from an inbound BNSF intermodal train, the assigned driver moving trailer RDWY 124099 to the intermodal parking area observed a black paint like substance at the trailer's rear doorway. RDWY 124099 was taken to the facility's containment area for lading inspection. Contract responders found two 5 gallon pails stowed near the doorway partially crushed by palletized heavy lading stacked atop these pails. The commodity in these pails escaped from the damaged top lid area. Responders over-packed the damaged pails, cleaned the spillage inside RDWY 124099 and reworked the lading at the rear end of the trailer.   Also, methods of securement to prevent cargo migration during transit were not observed in RDWY 124099.
column169: Ensure shipper's LTL shipments are properly blocked and braced for transportation and that lading arrangements comply with acceptable procedures to avoid lading damage in transit.

column168: Univar driver was making a delivery to customer when noticed one drum of waste (from another generator) was leaking.  Driver notified customer and leak was contained by use of absorbent socks and placing leaking drum into an overpack container.  Univar management dispatched an emergency response contractor to scene and also traveled to the scene to manage the response.  Approximately two gallons of material leaked from the drum over an appromimately 10 minute period.  Emergency response contractor arrived, cleaned material from floor of truck, and cleaned customers pavement using degreaser, absorbent material, and pressure washing.  All cleanup materials were contained and removed to seperate waste drums. A small hole was found in the bottom of the container, similiar in size to the nails used in pallet construction.    The cause of the leak was determined to be a puncture by one of the nails used to construct the pallet.  A slight side shift in the drums and vibration of the moving truck were determined as the means of puncture.
column169: Although the load was both blocked and load locked, the width of the trailer allowed a slight movement to the side in the drums.  Additional strapping and blocking will be added to loads to avoid recurrance.

column168: Sections of steel pipe, contaminated with chromium, were loaded into a rolloff container by dropping them from an excavator.  In this process a section of the rolloff floor suffered a crack.  After loading, the rolloff container was placed in an area that was being irrigated and a small amount of water entered the rolloff container.  The container was transported to the carrier's Bartow, FL terminal without incident where it was placed into temporary storage on a concrete containment pad.  The next morning it was discovered that approximately 5 gallons of water had leaked out of the container onto the containment pad and had contaminated approximately 200 gallons of standing rain water that was on the containment pad.  The contaminated rain water and approximately 100 gallons of rinse water were pumped into drums for disposal.  The crack in the container floor was repaired on site.
column169: It should be noted that heavy sections of steel pipe are likely to cause damage if they are simply dropped from above into a steel container.  Loading operators must be made aware of this.

column168: FIRST, THERE WAS NO FAILURE OF THE TRUCK-MOUNTED LIQUID TANK. THE ERROR WAS CAUSED BY THE DRIVER FAILING TO PROPERLY NEGOTIATE THE EXIT OFF THE INTERSTATE. HE SWERVED AT THE LAST SECOND AND THE REAR BUMPER OF THE VEHICLE CLIPPED THE LEFT FRONT BUMPER OF ANOTHER VEHICLE, CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO SWERVE AND HIT AGAINST THE GUARD RAIL ON THE DRIVER SIDE. TO ATTEMPT TO COMPENSATE, THE DRIVER TRIED TO CORRECT THE ACTION AND THAT CAUSED THE VEHICLE TO SWERVE ACROSS THE EXIT RAMP AND HIT AGAINST THE RIGHT SIDE GUARD RAIL WHERE THE VEHICLE CAME TO REST ON ITS SIDE. THE VEHICLE WAS QUICKLY RIGHTED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONSE TEAM. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DID NOT WANT THE VEHICLE MOVED FURTHER OR TOWED UNTIL THEY WERE ASSURED THERE WAS NO BREACH OR LEAKAGE FROM THE LIQUID TANK. THE COMPANY BROUGHT SEVERAL PATIENT-READY STATIONARY LIQUID BASE TANKS VIA ANOTHER VEHICLE AND FILLED THEM SUCESSFULLY FROM THE TRUCK-MOUNTED TANK WITH INCIDENT. AT THAT POINT, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDERS REALIZED THERE WAS NO HAZMAT DANGER, AND THEY ALLOWED THE VEHICLE TO BE TOWED FOR FURTHER ASSESSMENT AND REPAIR. NEITHER THE OTHER VEHICLE OR THE DRIVER OF THAT VEHICLE WERE DAMAGED OR INJURED. THE EXIT ROADWAY WAS CLOSED AS A PRECAUTION UNTIL THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDERS WERE CONFIDENT THE VEHICLE COULD BE TOWED AND THE EXIT RAMP RE-OPENED. NO SPILLS, NO RELEASE, NO FAILURES, NO INJURIES. SIMPLE HUMAN ERROR CAUSED BY AN INATTENTIVE DRIVER WHO FAILED TO RECOGNIZE THE APPROACHING EXIT IN TIME. THIS ONLY CONSIDERED A HAZMAT INCIDENT BECAUSE THERE WAS LIQUID OXYGEN ON BOARD. NEITHER THE CONTAINER OR THE PRODUCT WERE AFFECTED AS A RESULT OF THIS ACCIDENT. THE BOX TRUCK BODY SUSTAINED CONSIDERABLE DAMAGE.
column169: THE DRIVER FAILED TO PAY ATTENTION EARLY ENOUGH TO HIS GPS DEVICE, AND HE REACTED POORLY CAUSING THE ACCIDENT. THIS WAS AN ISOLATED CIRCUMSTANCE AND IS NOT PART OF ANY SYSTEMATIC PROBLEM.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Vehicle was traveling westbound on SR 44.  For no known reason, the driver left the paved surface of the roadway.  The road shoulder surface was soft grass and soil which sloped sharply down away from the road surface.  Though the steer never got more than 2' off the roadway, the load momentum caused the trailer wheels down approximately 3' into the roadside ditch, subsequently impacting a concrete driveway culvert.  The impact tore off the front set of dual tandems, complete with axle and suspension components.  The force of the impact appears to have launched the combined tractor trailer unit laterally causing it to land on a subsequent paved driveway on its starboard (right) side.  As the trailer slid across the drive, a gash was torn into the cargo tank shell of compartment 1, and broke off the pressure releif valve on compartment 2.  Both compartments emptied their contents onto the soil.  Connersville EMS responded almost immediately to the scene and closed the road, attended to the driver, and evacuated 8 homes in the immediate vicinity.  The Fire Department laid fire suppression foam onto the scene to minimize risks from volatile flammable components while private emergency response contractors were mustered to the scene.  Response contractor acted to remove the remaining contents of the cargo tank compartments to a staged cargo tank.  The damaged tractor trailer combo was then righted by a wrecker crew and towed from the scene to the wrecker yard.  Emergency response efforts were immediately taken to dig up the impacted soils and minimize the risks to the adjacent residences.  Emergency response and remediation efforts remain ongoing at the time of this report.
column169: Driver training to reinforce the consequences of leaving the roadway surface.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On 06/18/2013, at 2119, personnel in the CSXT Pascagoula Mississippi Yard discovered CPDX 102088, a residue tank car of LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GASES, leaking from pressure relief device. The car was isolated and the shipper Nova Chemicals Canada LTD, Mississippi EMA, NRC were notified.  CHEMTREC was not listed as the emergency contact. The shipper listed their own emergency contact number. United States Environmental Services, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found vapor being released from the presure relief valve.O ring was found to be not seated in the retainer cap groove. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Kevin Deangles, Nova Chemical 412-977-6933. Contractor personnel reseated the oring in the retaining cap and secured the presure relief device. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move. 7.1 is required.    Cause Code: 413  NARRI: 2(4+5+0) x (2+0)=36

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Svc at Clean Harbor’s in transit facility in Bridgeport NJ for the purpose of consolidating less than  truck load quantities of hazardous waste for continuing transportation to the intended waste management facility. While transferring one container  approximately 1 pint of material escaped from a puncture hole on the body of the drum.Facility personnel placed the leaking container into a suitable  salvage drum along with all clean-up debris from the van trailer. The container was secured and was sent for disposal to the intended waste management  facility.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. The driver, however, was re-instructed to conduct a  thorough inspection of each container before acceptance and if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take appropriate action to  either place the container into a suitable salvage drum or re containerize before transportation is initiated. In addition, the shipper was advised of the  incident and was requested to inspect all drums in current inventory for any containers with suspect integrity.

When ACFX 76513 cam einto the Harvey Railyard it was noticed to have Product on the exterior of the tank car, CP set the car out and notified the DG Person on call. WHEN I GOT INTO THE TRAILER THERE WAS NOTICEABLE IRRITATION OF MY EYES, NOSE AND THROAT FROM THE FUMES I LEFT THE TRAILER IMMEDIATELY AND RETURNED WITH THE SCBA. WEARING PPE AND SCBA, I UNLOADED THE TRAILER, REMOVED THE LEAKER AND THE LEAKED-ON PACKAGES, RETURNED TO THE CLERK STAITON TO FINISH CLEANING UP THE SPILL AND PROCESS THE HAZMAT.
column169: THE INCIDENCE WOULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED IF THE HAZARDOUS PACKAGE WAS PROPERLY LOADED THE PACKAGE WOULDN'T HAVE LEAKED IF IT WAS UPRIGHT. SINCE IT WAS LAYING ON ITS SIDE DURING TRANSIT, THE LIQUID CONTENTS INSIDE THE BOX SPILLED, CAUSING IRRITABLE FUMES AS WELL AS DAMAGED PACKAGES.

column168: DISCOVERED PACKAGE LEFT ON SHELF IN DMP WHEN ARRIVED AT 4:00AM. BJ" PACKAGE HAD NOT BEEN OPENED TO SEE IF PRODUCT INSIDE WAS LEAKING. RESPONDED TO PACKAGE USING DECISION TREE AND WEARING GOOGLES, BOOTS, APRON AND NITRILE GLOVES WITH THE SILVER SHIELD INNER LINER. PACKAGE ALSO HAD SHIPPING PAPERS AND A DIAMOND HAZARD LABEL CORROSIVE 8. OPENED PACKAGE AND SAW THAT TWO OF FOUR PRODUCTS WERE LEAKING FROM LOOSE CAPS AND SOILED AND STAINED. USED THE CORROSIVE LIQUIDS AND SOLIDSRESPONSE SHEET TO PROCESS MATERIAL THROUGH DMP AND HAD SONYA (RMP) RETURN UNDAMAGED MATERIAL IN A SALVAGE DRUM.

column168: Landstar contacted ERTS in regards to a leaking tote on a trailer at the referenced location. ERTS dispatched FMS to the site and they transferred the material from the damaged tote into a new tote. They then unloaded the cargo, cleaned up the trailer floor with absorbents along with a small area of impacted pavement at the truck stop. All waste was containerized and transported off site for pending disposal. The cargo was then reloaded onto the trailer to continue on to the consignee.

Shipment blocked and braced only partially on only one side.  Full sheet was placed on 1 side but was not as tall as the skid.  Strap was run around skid, but boxes were allowed to shift.  It also appears as if boxes had already shifted prior to loading.  Several boxes were not loaded with orientation labels upright.  Leaking box was on bottom of skid on blocked side and was laid over in addition to other boxes in that same area.  Had loader taken the time to restack the skid prior to loading, the bottles likely would not have leaked.  Cleaned up in house.

column168: After arrival on an inbound BNSF intermodal train, intermodal container TGHU 969851 containing mixed hazardous material lading was reported leaking an unknown liquid substance. TGHU 969851 was carefully moved to the facility's containment area and placed over protective sheeting for a detailed inspection by contract responders. Responders reported one IBC found with a broken outer steel frame structure that had pierced and cut the top center sidewall of the plastic inner receptacle of this IBC. This remaining commodity (Concentrated Alkaline Liquid Cleaner) within this damaged IBC was transferred to another suitable IBC and properly labeled.   During the lading removal from TGHU 969851 for cleaning, two additional IBC's with a different corrosive hazardous material were noted leaking due to cuts in their inner plastic receptacles. These two IBC's were also transferred to other suitable IBC's. All other lading within TGHU 969851 was inspected and when necessary, cleaned of any spillage. Afterwards, all lading was placed into another intermodal container and secured for furtherance in highway transportation. TGHU 969851 was removed from the intermodal facility and taken to the responder's facility for additional floor cleaning. All generated waste and spent cleaning materials were earmarked for appropriate disposal.
column169: No additional comments.
column172: Composite, with a rigid plastic inner receptacle for liquids and a steel outer packaging

column168: Driver stopped for a break and noticed product dripping from box around internal valve. A bucket was placed under internal valve and release was captured at a rate of approximately 2 drips per minute.  Environmental emergency response crew was dispatched to the scene; an attempt to tighten sum bolts failed and shipment was transferred to another cargo tank trailer.  When emptied the trailer was returned to La Porte Texas and the interior was clean at an outside tank wash. After cleaning the trailer was filled with water and pressurized in an attempt to find the leak. After 30 minutes no leak was discovered. The trailer was filled with 50,000 pounds of water put under pressure and set over night with no leak discovered. Trailer was returned to service with no further issues.
column169: Procedures were reviewed with mechanics and the sump bolts tested and were tightened to proper setting.

column168: Supplier failed to report cargo as being hazardous. We then looked at the documentation and it seems cargo was originally consigned to another freight forwarder which also raised a flag to us. column168: UTLX 23394 was found with product leaking from the top of the car and down both sides by the inbound car dept.  Chip Heard, MHM, contacted United States Environmental Services to respond.  Upon arrival the car was inspected and found to be leaking at the four bolt flange under the liquid valve.  All four bolts on the flange were finger loose.  The bolts were all properly tool tightened and the leak stopped.  Approximately 10 gallons of product was released.  The car was wiped clean and placed in hold status in the local yard.  The car was inspected on 6/13/2013 and no leak observed.  The shipper obtained an OTMA-3 and the car was released back into transportation.

column168: A BNSF train was stopped by a FRA Railroad Safety Inspector to inspect an entrained tank car that appeared to be leaking commodity from its manway closure. Entrained tank car GATX 201648 was identified. BNSF operating and mechanical hazardous material responders inspected GATX 201648 and reported commodity staining that emanated from the manway closure. The manway securement bolts were all tool tight. The manway gasket was inspected and appeared to be compressed and not providing a good closure seal due to the manway securement bolts being over-torqued. The responders resecured the manway lid and properly tool tightened the manway securement bolts in the appropriate pattern. Afterwards, the BNSF train was released to proceed.

column42: ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, N.O.S., AT OR ABOVE 100 C AND BELOW ITS FLASH POINT (INCLUDING MOLTEN METALS, MOLTEN SALTS, ETC.)
column168: On 06/20/2013 at 11:45 , personnel in the CSXT Rice Yard, Waycross GA, discovered UTLX 644030, a residue tank car of Elevated Temperature Liquid N.O.S., Petroleum Asphalt, leaking from the bottom outlet. The car was isolated and the shipper and chemtrec were notified. (CHEMTREC Report #2013-06-20-00134. Josh winters, a CSXT mechanical manager, was on scene and found the bottom outlet valve handle not pinned in the closed position, the bottom outlet cap less than tool tight and product leaking from around the cap. He also found the manway proped open by a manway bolt. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Ray Callahan 229 248-0804.The bottom outlet valve was closed and secured and the bottom outlet cap and the manway were secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required    Cause Code:148  NARRI:5(4+1+0) x (2+0) = 50
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Tank car FURX 120102 was reported leaking commodity prior to rail interchange delivery in the railyard and accordingly was refused by receiving carrier. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected FURX 120102 and reported the liquid line closure flange had loose securement bolts which allowed commodity to escape at this flange connection. Responder tool tightened all four securement bolts up to 4 turns each which ended any further commodity release by 2000 hrs. CDT, 6/23/2013. Spillage on FURX 120102 was neutralized with residual spillage wiped. A small amount of spillage atop the ballast was also neutralized.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On June 23, 2013, at 09:23 hours, a car inspector at the CSXT New Castle Yard, New Castle, PA noticed the bottom outlet valve leaking on UTLX 200863, a loaded tank car of UN1987, Alcohols N.O.S.. The tank car was isolated. The shipper, Cardinal Ethanol, was notified via Chemtrec, report #2013-06-2300009 . SPSI, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the New Castle Yard. SPSI found the bottom outlet valve in a partially open position and the bottom outlet assembly less than tool tight at the four inch threads of the tank car. The shipper representative, Jeremy Herlyn 765-914-4938, was notified of the situation found. The release was secured and UTLX 200863 was released for disposition after the internal bottom outlet valve was deemed to be working properly.  This incident did not require a special move.    NARRI: 5x(5+1+0)x(2+0) = 60  Cause code:551

column168: At 10:30 DSR opened up the trailer.  One of the totes, the release valve had come off. Some of the corrosive material spilled onto the floor of the trailer. We were able to find the valve and reatach. The DSR then cleaned up the trailer.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURED. WHILE TRAVELING, VEHICLE WAS INVOLVED IN AN ACCIDENT, WHICH CAUSED TRUCK TO ROLLOVER AND RESULT IN SUBSEQUENT TRAILER FIRE. KANSAS CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT AND MISSOURI DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE. HIGHWAY WAS SHUTDOWN FOR APPROXIMATELY 16 HOURS DURING RECOVERY AND REMEDIATION EFFORTS. FD APPLIED FOAM AND WATER TO EXTINGUISH FIRE AND MINIMIZE VAPORS FROM BURNING PRODUCT. APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF DOWANOL, AND APPROXIMATELY 1,681 GALLONS OF PROPYL ACETATE WERE RELEASED FROM THE TRAILER COMPARTMENTS. MISSOURI DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES AND USEPA RESPONDED TO OVERSEE RESPONSE EFFORTS. A DYKE WAS CREATED WITH ROADSIDE SOILS TO PREVENT MIGRATION OF RUNOFF WATERS. TWIN CREEK ENVIROMENTAL OF KANSAS CITY, KANSAS WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. UPON ARRIVAL ON SITE, TWIN CREEK ENVIROMENTAL DISCUSSED PLAN OF ACTION ALONG WITH MODNR AND USEPA. TWIN CREEK ENVIROMENTAL ASSISTED IN DYKING THE AREA AND USED A VACUUM TRUCK TO RECOVER THE FREE LIQUIDS AND RUNOFF FROM THE FD SUPPRESSANT. HULCHER SERVICES WAS CONTRACTED TO TRANSFER THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE DAMAGED VEHICLE TO A RECOVERY TANKER. APPROXIMATELY 6,500 GALLONS OF CONTAMINATED WATERS, AND ONE (1) ROLLOFF OF SOILS WERE GENERATED DURING THE CLEANUP. BOOM WAS LEFT DOWNGRADIENT FROM THE INCIDENT SITE, AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE, AND NO FURTHER ACTION WAS REQUIRED. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.
column169: LANGER TRANSPORT WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING PROCEDURES AND DRIVER SAFETY TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: THE ROSS EXPRESS DRIVER PICKED UP 4 DRUMS ON (1) WOODEN PALLET OF FORMALDEHYDE AND LOADED BY GM SPECIALTIES IN SCARBOROUGH, ME AND OUR DRIVER SECURED THE DRUMS IN THE TRAILER WITH A NYLON STRAP TO THE TRAILER WALL. WHEN HE ARRIVED AT HIS NEXT CUSTOMER - SHAW'S SUPERMARKETS IN WELLS, ME, HE NOTICED THERE WAS WETNESS ON AN AREA OF THE TRAILER FLOOR FROM A DRUM ON A PALLET IN BACK OF TRAILER NEAR THE BACK DOOR. HE LOOKED CLOSER AND NOTICED THE DRUM IN QUESTION HAD MOVED ON THE WOODEN PALLET AND CAUGHT A NAIL CAUSING A SMALL HOLE. THE NAIL WAS STICKING UP OFF THE WOODEN PALLET THE DRUM WAS RESTING ON CAUSING IT TO LEAK. SOME PRODUCT LEAKED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE ESTIMATED PRODUCT LOSS FROM THE PLASTIC DRUM TO BE APPROX. -5 GALLONS FROM THE 55 GALLON CONTAINER ONCE HE WAS ABLE TO DO A TEMPORARY REPAIR. THE FREIGHT ON THE WOODEN PALLET WAS PREPARED BY GM SPECIALTIES. THE FUMES FROM THE PRODUCT WERE VERY HEAVY NOT ALLOWING ANYONE INTO THE TRAILER FOR ANY LENGTH OF TIME. WHEN OUR DRIVER WAS AT THE CUSTOMER'S DOCK THE CUSTOMER REFUSED THEIR FREIGHT AND WOULD NOT ALLOW ANY EMPLOYEES INTO THE TRAILER DUE THE FUMES. CUSTOMER-SHAW'S IN WELLS, ME CALLED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT/CAPT. AND STATE OF MAINE - DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION/SCOTT CYR, THEY WERE INVOLVED DURING THE CLEAN UP PROCESS. THE PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP WITH SPEEDY DRY MATERIAL AND DRUM SEALED FOR TRANSPORT BACK TO GM SPECIALTIES IN SCARBOROUGH, ME. THE WASTE MATERIAL PART OF THE PRODUCT WAS DISPOSED OF BY WELLS FIRE DEPARTMENT AND 55 GALLON DRUM WAS RETURNED TO GM SPECIALTIES. THE DISPOSAL OF THE DRUM WITH REMAINING PRODUCT WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK BY WELLS FIRE DEPARTMENT AND DELIVERED BACK TO GM SPECIALTIES. AFTER THE DRIVER RETURNED TO NH TERMINAL THE TRAILER WAS PLACED OUT OF SERVICE IN A SECURED YARD AND LEFT TO VENTILATE. EXTRA CLEANING MATERIAL HAS BEEN USED FOR CLEAN OUT OF TRAILER.
column169: DRIVER IS A CURRENT COMPANY HM TRAINED EMPLOYEE AND A CURRENT HM TRAINED VOLUNTEER FIRE FIGHTER IN HIS LOCAL CITY IN NH. HE HANDLED THE HM INCIDENT PER COMPANY POLICIES WITH REGARD TO HM SPILL RESPONSE PROCEDURES. HE FOLLOWED INSTRUCTIONS FROM ROSS EXPRESS, INC. DISPATCH TO PROTECT HIMSELF FIRST AND KEEP OTHERS AWAY FROM HM SPILL LOCATION. HE NOTIFIED OUR COMPANY ABOUT THE PRODUCT AND THE SITUATION WITH THE DAMAGE/LEAK TO THE DRUM. column168: AFTER THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE HE PREPARED TO UNLOAD. HE CONNECTED HIS CARGO HOSES, VENTED THE TANK, AND AS A PRECAUTION HE PLACED A DRIP BUCKET UNDER HIS CARGO PUMP. WHEN HE BEGAN TO PUMP OFF THE MATERIAL A SMALL DRIP DEVELOPED FROM THE DISCHARGE PIPE ON HIS CARGO PUMP. FORTUNATELY, ALL OF THE DRIPPING MATERIAL WAS CAPTURED IN THE DRIP BUCKET. NO MATERIAL WAS RELEASED ONTO THE GROUND. A MECHANIC WAS SENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. HE TIGHTENED THE PIPE AS MUCH AS HE COULD WITHOUT STRIPPING THE THREADS. HE WAS ABLE TO SLOW THE DRIP AND THE CONSIGNEE DECIDED THAT AS LONG AS THE DRIP WAS BEING CAPTURED IN THE DRIP BUCKET TO CONTINUE THE UNLOADING PROCESS. AFTER UNLOADING WAS COMPLETED THERE WAS LESS THAN ONE GALLON OF MATERIAL IN THE DRIP BUCKET AND THE CONSIGNEE TOOK POSSESSION OF IT.
column169: SUBSEQUENT INVESTIGATION REVEALED MINUTE BURRS ON THE DISCHARGE PIPE THREAD THAT ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO LEAK FROM THE DISCHARGE PIPE CONNECTION TO THE PUMP HOUSING. ALL PUMP INSTALLATIONS ARE CHECKED PRIOR  TO RELEASING TO OPERATIONS FOR WORK  TO ENSURE THAT THEY DO NOT LEAK. SUCH WAS THE CASE IN THE APPLICATION. THIS NEW PUMP INSTALLATION WAS USED IN THE TRANSFERRING WATER WHICH THE NEWLY TRAINED DRIVER IMPLEMENTED IN AN EFFORT TO DEMONSTRATE HIS SKILLS TO OUR DRIVER TRAINER. THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF THIS PUMP LEAKING DURING THAT PROCESS, THEREFORE, DRIVER AND EQUIPMENT WERE RELEASED FOR WORK. MOVING FORWARD, ALL MECHANICS INVOLVED IN THE INSTALLATION OF EQUIPMENT, I.E PUMPS, HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO PAY CLOSE ATTENTION TO THE THREADING OF INTAKE AND DISCHARGE PIPES.

column168: DRIVER WAS EN ROUTE BACK TO THE MIDLAND SITE FROM A EXPLOSIVES SHOT IN CARLSBAD, TEXAS. AS HE PASSED THROUGH GARDEN CITY, HE WAS ABOUT 2.4 MILES WEST WHEN HE LOOKED DOWN AT THE DASH, WAS TRAVELING ABOUT 70 AND LOOKED BACK UP REALIZING THAT HE HAD DRIVEN OFF THE ROAD TO THE RIGHT. HE ATTEMPTED TO CORRECT THIS SITUATION AND BRING THE VEHICLE BACK ON THE ROADWAY BUT STRUCK A SHORT CULVERT WITH THE DRIVER SIDE STEERING TIRE. THE VEHICLE THEN BEGAN TO GO TO THE LEFT AND BACK ON THE ROADWAY STILL TURNING TO THE LEFT AND THEN ABRUPTLY TO THE RIGHT AND OVERTURNING ONTO ITS LEFT SIDE STOPPING PARTIALLY ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE PAVED AND DIRT SHOULDERS... THIS BED WAS A FEED TYPE BED AND THE DOOR HATCHES (3) CAME OPEN AND SPILLED APPROXIMATELY 100 LBS OF AN PRILL. THERE WAS ALSO AND OFF ROAD TANK ATTACHED TO THE BACK OF THE BINS IT DID NOT RUPTURE. ONLY FLUIDS THAT SPILLED WERE HYDRAULIC. THE AMMONIUM NITRATE (AN) WAS IN PRILL FORM AND DID NOT CAUSE ANY ENVIRONMENTAL PROBLEMS. CLEANUP WAS CONDUCTED BY THE GARDEN CITY VFD SINCE IT WAS ONLY AN AND HAD NO DIESEL MIXED INTO IT.
column169: ADDITONAL TRAINING WAS CONDUCTED ON THE DRIVER AND ALL EMPLOYEES AT THE SITE. RETRAINING WAS CONDUCTED IN ACCORDANCE WITH PHMSA SPECIAL PERMIT 11579 AND TOPICS WERE ROLLOVER TRAINING AWARENESS, DOT VEHICLE RECOVERY, SPECIAL PERMIT TRAINING, DROWSY DRIVING, BPC PROFESSIONAL DRIVER SOP.

column168: The driver made a delivery of Hypochlorite CSS-10 to Metropolitan St. Louis Sewer District in St. Louis.  He asked the operator there if the load would fit into the tank and the operator said that it would.  As the trailer was getting to the end of unloading, the customer’s tank overflowed.  The driver shut down the unloading.  The release was into containment and the operator said that it was not a big deal.    When the driver got to the facility he looked at the tank reading to see if the tank would hold the full amount. The tank read 1420.  The tank capacity is 6000 gallons and the trailer had 4650 gallons.  The driver told the operator that there wasn’t enough room but the operator said that they were pulling product out of the tank while we were loading so that it would fit.  The driver took precautions and stood close to the end of the trailer so that he could shut the valve off quickly if necessary.  Just as the hose started jumping (which signals the trailer is going empty) the product started coming out of the tank.  The driver couldn’t see the release because it was coming out of the back of the tank top, but he could hear it, so he shut it off.  There was about 10-15 gallons of hypochlorite spilled in containment.  The driver asked the operator what he wanted him to do, and the operator said not to worry about it, that it was all in containment.  Another operator commented that when they draw out of the tank that it doesn’t come out very fast which is why it overflowed.
column169: The driver saw that there wasn’t enough room and made a poor judgment in deciding to allow the operator to convince him that it would fit.  He should bring back product if it doesn’t fit.  Driver will use own judgment and not be persuaded by others.

column168: A vehicle containing hazardous waste was enroute to its disosal destination. During transport a 20 gallon drum was tipped over and proceeded to leak from the closure. The driver righted the drum to stop the leakage and called his manager, local fire and police. A response team was mobilized to the scene for clean up and using appropriate personnel protective equipment cleaned up the leaked material. All materials used in the clean-up of the van were properly package and then the drums were secured for continued transportation. After inspection of load securement the Florida State Police released the van for continued transpotation.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. The driver, however, was re-instructed to conduct a  thorough inspection of each load and to insure proper load securement is done.

column168: Tank car GATX 17823 was reported leaking in the railyard from its top fitting area. GATX 17823 was cordoned-off in the railyard awaiting inspection from BNSF and contract hazardous material responders. The responder's inspection revealed the leak source was at the liquid valve's bolted pipe flange connection. The internal pressure within GATX 17823 was reduced which ended the commodity release at this valve's pipe flange connection. Spillage was evaporating rapidly. Responder's tool tightened all four flange bolt nuts approximately three turns each to secure this flange connection and eliminated any further commodity leaks. All spillage evaporated.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column169: DRIVER WAS RETRAINED IN DELIVERING OF FUEL AND HOW TO DELIVER WITHOUT SPILLING ANY FUEL, AND TO DOUBLE CHECK ON AMOUNT THAT CAN BE DELIVERED SO THAT THERE NOT BE ANY OVER FILLING OF PRODUCTS.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS DELIVERING 7804 GALLONS OF REGULAR UNLEADED INTO A 12,000 GALLON TANK. UPON MEASURING THE PRODUCT IN THE BELOW GROUND TANK, THE DRIVER DISCOVERED THERE WAS 3287 GALLONS. THE DRIVER DECIDED TO DROP ALL 7804 GALLONS INTO THE BELOW GROUND TANK. THE TANK HE WAS DELIVERING INTO HAS AN OVER FILL PROTECTION SHUTOFF SET AT 90% (10,800 GALLONS). WHILE DROPPING HIS LAST COMPARTMENT OF REGULAR GASOLINE, THE DRIVER FILLED THE TANK PAST 90% AND REALIZED THE FLOW OF PRODUCT HAD STOPPED AND HAD BACKED UP IN THE DROP HOSE. HE THEN PROCEEDED TO UNHOOK THE DROP HOSE TO ALLOW SOME OF THE PRESSURE TO RELEASE FROM THE TANK. AS A RESULT OF THE BACK PRESSURE, PRODUCT BEGAN SHOOTING BACK OUT OF THE TANK THROUGH THE DROP HOSE. APPROXIMATELY RAN 100 FEET DOWN THE CONCRETE PARKING LOT INTO STORM DRAIN. ALL OF THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED WITH THE STORM DRAIN. ALONG WITH THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. WE CHECKED THE STORM DRAIN FURTHER DOWN TO CONFIRM THE PRODUCT DIDN'T GRAVITATE TO THE NEXT DRAINAGE AREA. IN FACT,THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT IN THE INITIAL STORM DRAIN DIDN'T REACH A LEVEL HIGH ENOUGH TO ENTER THE PIPING THAT EXITS INTO THE NEXT DRAIN. UPON REMOVING THE GRATE COVERING THE INITIAL DRAIN, WE USED THE PUMP ON OUR DELIVERY TRUCK TO REMOVE THE PRODUCT IN THE DRAIN. APPROXIMATELY 15-20 GALLONS WERE REMOVED. THE PRODUCT ON THE CONCRETE WAS REMOVED WITH A SMALL NUMBER OF SPILL PADS. THE PRODUCT REMOVED VIA PUMP WAS PUT INTO A DRAIN DOWN TANK LOCATED AT THE KEYSTONE OFFICE, WHERE IT WILL EVENTUALLY BE RE-DELIVERED TO ALLIED ENERGY CORPORATION FOR RECYCLING.
column169: KEYSTONE PETROLEUM TANSPORT'S STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURES ARE TO NEVER FILL AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK BEYOND 90% OF THE TANK'S CAPACITY. THE DRIVER WAS ISSUES A VIOLATION NOTICE, SUPSENDED WITHOUT PAY, AND RETRAINED ON OUR COMPANY'S DELIVERY PROCEDURES.

column168: While at the consignee for unloading, product was noticed streaked on the outside of the cargo tank.  It appears the front washout cap was cross threaded.  Driver had pretripped the trailer when he picked it up loaded.  He said the washout cap was tight and he didn't notice it was cross-threaded at that time.  He did not notice any leakage enroute.  No cars or trucks flagged him down.  He did not leave a trail going into the consignee.  It may have been a slow leak that stuck to the trailer.  Product was thick.  The unload was completed.  Since the washout cap was secured properly, the product on the trailer was sticky and was not in any danger of running off, and the customer did not have room in their yard, the trailer was taken to a nearby truckstop to be cleaned off.  We contacted an emergency response vendor to clean it off.  No indication that any product hit the ground.
column169: we regularly address the issue of cross-threaded washout caps with our drivers via in-truck messages and training.

column168: ONE CYLINDER CONTAINING RESIDUAL PHOSPHINE DEVELOPED A SMALL LEAK DURING TRANSPORTATION. THE LEAK RESULTED IN THE PRODUCTION OF DIPHOSPHORUS PENTOXIDE, WHICH WAS VISIBLE AS WHITE SMOKE. UPON NOTICING THE LEAK, THE DRIVER PULLED INTO AN ISOLATED TRUCK STOP LOCATION AND NOTIFIED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. BUSINESS PERSONNEL PROVIDED INSTRUCTION TO THE FIRE DEPARTMENT IN ORDER TO LOCATE AND ISOLATE THE SUBJECT CYLINDER. THE CYLINDER CAP WAS REMOVED AND THE VALVE WHEEL WAS TIGHTENED A 1/4 TURN, AS WAS THE GAS TIGHT PLUG, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. IT IS BELIEVED THAT VIBRATION OR MOVEMENT DURING TRANSPORTATION ALLOWED THE HAND WHEEL TO LOOSEN. THE GAS TIGHT PLUG WAS NOT SUFFICIENTLY TIGHTENED, WHICH ALLOWED THE SMALL RELEASE OF PHOSPHINE GAS THAT PRODUCED DIPHOSPHORUS PENTOXIDE IN THE AIR. THE CYLINDER WAS RE-SECURED AFTER CONFIRMATION THAT IT WAS NOT LEAKING. IT WAS THEN PUT IN AN OVER PACK AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE AND SENT BACK TO THE ORIGINATING FACILITY FOR INVESTIGATION. NO EXPOSURE OR EVACUATION OCCURRED.
column169: THE OPERATING PROCEDURE FOR RETURNING THE RESIDUAL PRODUCTS OF PHOSPHINE BACK TO THE SUPPLIER HAS BEEN MODIFIED TO INCLUDE THE USE OF A ZIP TIE ON THE HAND WHEEL TO PREVENT THE POSSIBILITY OF LOOSENING DUE TO VIBRATION. IN ADDITION, THE PROCEDURE CLARIFIES INSTRUCTIONS ON THE PROPER TIGHTENING OF THE GAS TIGHT PLUG.

column168: Martin Transport trailer 7041, loaded with nitric acid, was parked in combination with Martin Transport tractor 3948 at the Relay Truck Stop in Greenwood, La. Before resuming his trip the driver performed a walk around of the equipment and noticed product dripping slowly from the trailer. The driver placed a bucket under the drip to contain the drips of product. Less than 1 gallon of nitric acid was released to the parking lot of the truck stop before the leak was detected. The duration of the leak is unknown. The incident was reported to the Louisiana State Police (case # 13-02733) and USES was called out for emergency response clean up and to transfer the product from the leaking trailer into another Martin Transport trailer. The leaking trailer was taken for testing and inspection to determine the location and cause of the leak where it was discovered that the trailer was leaking at the ring at the front of the dome box and where the clean out nipple is welded in the tank.
column169: Lap repairs will not be utilized on any DOT trailer.    Internal inspections and leak tests will be performed on all trailers in corrosive service at least annually. Trailers failing internal or leak tests will be removed from service to identify and record the cause of failure. The trailer will be repaired by a reputable R stamp shop. Following repairs, trailers will be leak tested before being returned to service.

column168: Tank car UTLX 208445 in the railyard was reported leaking commodity from its 165 psi Midland pressure relief device (PRD). UTLX 208445 was carefully moved and isolated over the railyard's track pan containment area. Inspection of UTLX 208445 revealed all valves and fittings were secure. The secured manway cover was opened to check commodity outage levels and it was observed that the level of outage was insufficient. Contract responders used a vacuum truck to reduce the lading within UTLX 208445 by approximately 2600 gallons without further incident which also ended the liquid release from the PRD. Afterwards, the shipper arranged to transfer the commodity from the vacuum truck to tank truck for furtherance. On 6/27/2013, commodity spillage on the exterior of UTLX 208445 was cleaned.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings, as well as, the attainment of appropriate commodity outages within the specified tank car.

column168: Driver stopped at truck stop and was doing a routine check of his load.  He noticed a small amount of liquid dripping from his trailer onto his truck's under carriage.  He immediately notified his supervisor, who notified Univar, the shipper.  Univar dispatched both Emergency Response contractor and Univar management to the scene.  Once response teams arrived at the scene, it was determined this small leak was caused by a cross treaded cap on one of the IBCs.  The amount of liquid lost was less than one gallon.  The liquid was cleaned from the under carriage of the trailer, and absorbed on the trailer floor.  No material reached the ground.  The lid was properly installed on the container.  Once the issue was corrected, and the spillage cleaned, the driver continued to his destination.
column169: As the spillage was caused by a cross threaded cap on a IBC, recommendation would center around a better process to ensure the proper closure of similiar containers.  Univar will use the incident as a training tool to insure increased diligence in inspecting containers for proper closure.

column168: A BRIEF OVERVIEW. MY TRANSPORTATION COMPANY, SCHOFF FARM SERVICE INC, DELIVERED A TRANSPORT LOAD OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA TO CONSEV FS IN ROCKFORD, ILLINOIS. IN PREPARATION TO UNLOAD, MY DRIVER STRUCK A LOW 10 FOOT UNMARKED OVERHEAD ANHYDROUS PIPE WHILE TRYING TO MANEUVER TO UNLOAD HIS TRANSPORT.  WHEN THE LIQUID LINE WAS STRUCK A 2 INCH LINE WAS CRACKED AND ANHYDROUS AMMONIA BEGAN TO RELEASE. THE QUICK RELEASE VALVE (IF PRESENT) DID NOT CLOSE.  THE DRIVER WENT TO THE STORAGE TANKS AND CLOSED ALL VALVES AND A 2 INCH LIQUID VALVE FEEDING THE LOAD RACK FAILED THERE AS WELL.  IF THE 3 INCH BELLY VALVE WOULD HAVE BEEN INSTALLED DIRECTLY AT THE BELLY OF THE STORAGE TANK IT WOULD HAVE STOPPED THE FLOW, HOWEVER; IT IS 12 TO 18 INCHES UNDER THE TANK WITH 2 INCH PLUMBING PIPED IN BETWEEN THE TANK BODY AND THE MAIN VALVE. (I HAVE NEVER SEEN THIS ANYWHERE.)  CONSERV HAD THREE MAJOR VALVE FAILURES IN MY OPINION:  1) QUICK RELEASE AT POINT OF IMPACT LOADING RACK  2) 2 INCH LIQUID VALVE AT STORAGE TANKS  3) THE 3 INCH BELLY VALVE WAS NOT PROPERLY INSTALLED ON THE STORAGE TANK.  I AM COMPLETING THIS FORM IN GOOD FAITH BECAUSE THE COOP, GROWMARK INC., AND CONSERV FS FEEL IT IS MY RESPONSIBILITY BECAUSE MY TRANSPORT MADE THE INITIAL CONTACT.  IN MY OPINION, CONSERV NEEDS TO COMPLY WITH THIS DOT 5800 FORM AS WELL SINCE THEIR COMPANY OWNED PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THEIR STORAGE TANKS.  NO PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM MY TRANSPORT.  IF THE COOP WOULD HAVE BEEN COMPLIANT IN SAFETY, CRASH CONTROL, AND MAINTENANCE THE INCIDENT WOULD BE NO MORE THAN A WAGON PULLING AWAY FROM AN APPLICATOR OR LOADING STATION.  A QUICK PUFF OF SMOKE AND WAITING A MINUTE FOR THE AIR TO CLEAR.  THAT HAPPENS OFTEN WHEN SAFETY VALVES WORK PROPERLY.  IN ESSENCE, THAT WOULD BE A NON-REPORTABLE INCIDENT DUE TO THE LIMITED AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RELEASED.    IN NO WAY DOES SCHOFF FARM SERVICE, INC. ACCEPT ANY RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE DAMAGES OTHER THAN THE PIPE THAT WAS BENT ON THE CUSTOMER'S PROPERTY.
column169: I WOULD LIKE TO COMMEND ALL THE VOLUNTEERS AND FIRST RESPONDERS FOR THEIR EFFORTS; HOWEVER, THEY ALL NEED SPECIFIC TRAINING UNDER THESE CIRCUMSTANCES. THE 100,000 GALLONS OF WATER DUMPED ON THIS LEAK CAUSED MORE DAMAGE THAN GOOD. THE COOP NEEDS TO CONSIDER WHERE THEIR RUNOFF GOES. THEY ALSO NEED TO PUT ALL LINES UNDERGROUND, NEVER OVERHEAD, AND IF SO PROTECT THEM WITH STRUCTURES SUCH AS CONCRETE OR GUARD RAILS! LOW OVERHEAD LINES NEED TO BE MARKED WITH SIGNS.  AS A CARRIER AND DRIVER FOR OVER 30 YEARS, I FEEL I HAVE A LOT TO OFFER THIS INDUSTRY WHEN IT COMES TO SAFETY AND HANDS ON COMMON SENSE. I AM HAPPY TO BE MORE COMPLETE OR PROVIDE DETAILS IF NEEDED.  WE FILLED OUT THE DOT 5800 TO BE BEST OF OUR ABILITY.  IF MORE INFORMATION IS NEEDED, WE WILL.

column168: CARGO TANK TRAILER TANK WAS LOADED AT CALUMET LUBRICANTS, SHREVEPORT,LA. CARGO TANK WAS LOADED BY DRIVER WITH SWEET VTB. DRIVER SECURED/LATCHED DOME LID AND ALL VALVES. THE DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO LOVE'S TRUCK STOP AT EXIT 3 ON I-20, GREENWOOD, LA. WHERE HE TOOK HIS BREAK AND WENT INTO THE SLEEPER. AT APPROXIMATELY 11.30PM A GREENWOOD POLICE OFFICER WOKE HIM UP, TOLD AND SHOWED HIM HIS TRAILER WAS LEAKING. AT APPROXIMATELY MIDNIGHT OUR DISPATCH WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY IN TURN NOTIFIED OUR SAFETY SUPERVISOR WHO IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED U.S.E.S. TO RESPOND AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL. ACCORDING TO POLICE THE AMOUNT SPILLED WAS 1 1/2 GALS. THE POLICE WOULD NOT ALLOW THE TRAILER TO BE MOVED SO ANOTHER ASPHALT TRANSPORT TRUCK AND TRAILER WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE SO THE PRODUCT COULD BE TRANSFERRED INTO THE SECOND TRUCK. AFTER THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED, THE SECOND TRUCK CONTINUED TO THE DELIVERY LOCATION. POLICE STILL WOULD NOT ALLOW THE LEAKING TRAILER TO BE MOVED. SEVERAL DAYS LATER THE LEAKING TRAILER WAS ALLOWED TO BE MOVED. IT WAS TAKEN TO A REPAIR SHOP IN CHANNELVIEW, TX. NO CITATIONS WERE ISSUED AT THE POINT AND TIME OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: ON 6/20/2013, AN EMPLOYEE OF CROP PRODUCTION SERVICES (CPS) WAS DELIVERING 2-1000 GALLON ANHYDROUS AMMONIA NURSE TANKS TO A LOCAL GROWER.  THE CPS DRIVER WAS NORTHBOUND ON IL ROUTE 4/ IL ROUTE 13, TRAVELLING 20-25 MPH. THE TANKS WERE TRANSPORTED IN TANDEM, ONE BEHIND THE OTHER. THE POWER UNIT WAS A 1999 FORD F350. THE VEHICLE FLASHERS WERE ACTIVATED. ALL SAFETY CHAINS WERE PROPERLY CONNECTED. THE DRIVER WAS WEARING HIS SEAT BELT. AS THE CPS DRIVER TRAVELED DOWN AN OVERPASS NEAR THE INTERSECTION OF IL ROUTE 4/ IL ROUTE 13 AND THE WASHINGTON COUNTY LINE ROAD, ANOTHER VEHICLE PULLED IN FRONT OF HIM. TO AVOID A SERIOUS VEHICLE ACCIDENT, THE CPS DRIVER SWERVED INTO THE LEFT LANE. THE REAR ANHYDROUS AMMONIA NURSE TANK BROKE OFF THE RUNNING GEAR. THE NURSE TANK ROLLED DOWN THE HIGHWAY AND CAME TO REST IN THE LEFT HAND DITCH.  THE FRONT TANK REMAINED ATTACHED TO THE VEHICLE/RUNNING GEAR AND DID NOT RECEIVE ANY DAMAGE. NO ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAS RELEASED FROM THE FRONT TANK.  DAMAGES TO THE REAR TANK INCLUDE: THE LIQUID FILL VALVE BROKE OFF, THE WITHDRAWAL VALVE AND THE VAPOR VALVE BOTH REMAINED IN PLACE BUT RECEIVED DAMAGE. ANHYDROUS AMMONIA BEGAN LEAKING FROM THE TANK.  911 WAS IMMEDIATELY CALLED. THE CALL WAS TRANSFERRED TO THE ILLINOIS STATE POLICE AND THEY DISPATCHED A UNIT TO THE SCENE. THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, STATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE AGENCY AND FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE NOTIFIED. THE TANK WITH THE RELEASE HAS BEEN HAS BEEN PERMANENTLY PLACED OUT OF SERVICE.
column169: ALTHOUGH THE 2 VEHICLE LISTED ON THE UNOFFICIAL TRAFFIC CRASH REPORT NEVER MADE CONTACT, THE ILLINOIS STATE POLICE LISTED THE OTHER VEHICLE FIRST ON THE REPORT. CROP PRODUCTION SERVICES IS IN THE PROCESS OF OBTAINING THE OFFICIAL REPORT.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 03:00 ON THE MORNING OF 6/27/2013, THE TRACTOR TRAILER DRIVEN BY ALEX BRENER WAS DRIVING SOUTHBOUND ON I-75 NEAR MM108 HAULING A TANKER LOAD OF 10.5% SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE (BLEACH). A 16 YEAR OLD GIRL IN A MINIVAN WAS STOPPED IN THE RIGHT HAND LANE FOR SOME REASON. THE TRACTOR TRAILER COLLIDED WITH THE REAR END OF THE MINIVAN WHICH PRECIPITATED A ROLLOVER WRECK. THE TRACTOR AND TANKER ROLLED MULTIPLE TIMES THROUGH THE MEDIAN BETWEEN I-75 AND EXIT 107 BEFORE COMING TO A STOP ACROSS THE EXIT ROADWAY. DURING THE ROLLOVER, THE DOME LID AND LOADING HATCH ON THE TANKER FAILED. THIS ALLOWED APPROX.3250 USG OF BLEACH TO ESCAPE THE TANKER. THE BLEACH RELEASED FROM THE TANKER RAN DOWN THE HILL INTO A STAGNANT SLOUGH. SODIUM THIOSULFATE WAS USED AT THE SITE TO NEUTRALIZE ANY SURFACE BLEACH ON THE ROAD. THIS WAS SWEPT UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF. SWS ENVIRONMENTAL HAS CONDUCTED REMEDIATION AT THE SITE, INCLUDING DIGGING UP AND REPLACING THE AFFECTED SOIL AND GRASS. AFTER SAMPLING SIGNIFICANTLY, SWS AND THE DEP OFFICIAL ON-SCENE DETERMINED NO NEGATIVE IMPACT TO THE WATER AND VEGETATION IN THE SLOUGH.

column169: KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE LOADING/UNLOADING PROTOCOL.

column168: On June 29, 2013, a New Century Transportation trailer experienced a release of UN1760 due to a cracked tote. An environmental contractor was dispatched and performed a tote transfer of the damaged tote. Absorbents were applied to the impacted trailer floor and worked in thoroughly. All contaminated material was containerized and placed on the trailer.

THE TOTE TANK WAS STRAPPED DOWN ON THE VEHICLE IN THE M-I SWACO YARD PRIOR TO LEAVING THE YARD. HOWEVER, THE HOOK ON THE STRAP WAS NOT PROPERLY SEATED AND CAME LOOSE AS THE DRIVER LEFT THE YARD. AS THE DRIVER EXITED THE YARD AND TURNED ONTO STOUT DRIVE, THE TOTE TANK FELL OFF THE TRAILER AND CRACKED SPILLING CHEMICAL ONTO THE ROAD. THE CHEMICAL WAS CONTAINED ON THE ROAD AND RECOVERED BY M-I SWACO PERSONNEL.
column169: INCIDENT TO BE DISCUSSED IN SAFETY MEETINGS WITH ALL OFFICES. ADDITIONAL TRAINING TO TAKE PLACE. GREATER EMPHASIS ON PRE-TRIP INSPECTIONS OF DOT VEHICLES. DISCIPLINARY ACTIONS WILL BE TAKEN ON EMPLOYEES WHO ARE NOT CONDUCTING PROPER INSPECTIONS OF VEHICLES PRIOR TO SHIPPING MATERIAL.

column14: NEW WATER PLANT ON CLERK ST
column168: WHEN CLIFF MALVEAUX, DRIVER FOR HARCROS CHEMICALS INC. ARRIVED TO MAKE HIS DELIVERY AT THE CITY OF MINDEN (C.O.M) STOREHOUSE, HE BACKED HIS TRAILER TO THE POSITION WHERE THE ATTENDANT INSTRUCTED HIM. WHEN HE WAS LOWERING A PALLET OF PRODUCT WITH THE LIFT-GATE ON HIS TRUCK, THE C.O.M. EMPLOYEE USED A PIECE OF PLYWOOD TO MAKE A BRIDGE BETWEEN OUR LIFT-GATE AND THEIR DOCK. WHEN THE C.O.M. EMPLOYEE TRIED TO ROLL THE CARBOY FROM THE PALLET ONTO THE DOCK, THE CARBOY FELL TO THE GROUND AND BURST SPILLING ALL BUT APPROXIMATELY 2.5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT ON THE GROUND. THE SUPERVISOR WAS NOTIFIED AND THE SPILLED CONTAINED.    ONCE THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED, THE C.O.M. EMPLOYEE CAME WITH A BACKHOE TO OFF LOAD THE REMAINDER OF THE CARBOYS INTO ITS BUCKET. CLIFF LINED HIS LIFT GATE UP AS EVEN AS POSSIBLE WITH THE BUCKET OF THE BACKHOE, BUT STILL HE HAD TO LIFT THE CARBOYS UP TO PLACE THEM INTO THE BUCKET. PICKING EACH CARBOY UP BY ITS HANDLE WITH TWO HANDS, HE LIFTED THE FIRST 2 WITHOUT ANY PROBLEM. WHEN HE ATTEMPTED TO LIFT THE NEXT ONE, THE TOP OF THE CARBOY GAVE WAY AND THE PRODUCT SPLASHED HITTING HIM IN HIS FACE AND SHOULDER. THE EMERGENCY UNIT WAS CALLED AND CLIFF WAS TAKEN TO MINDEN MEDICAL CENTER.
column169: THERE WERE TWO CONTAINERS DAMAGED DURING THIS INCIDENT.    THE FIRST CONTAINER INCIDENT WAS AS A RESULT OF OUR CUSTOMER'S EMPLOYEE. HARCROS CHEMICAL'S DISTRICT MANAGER, WAREHOUSE MANAGER AND CUSTOMER SALESMAN, WILL WORK WITH OUR CUSTOMER AND DETERMINE A SAFER WAY FOR THEM TO SAFELY REMOVE PRODUCT FROM OUT TRUCK DURING DELIVERIES.      THE SECOND CONTAINER INCIDENT WAS THE RESULT OD ACTIONS OF OUR DRIVER/EMPLOYEE. THE HANDLES ON THESE CONTAINERS ARE NOT MEANT TO BE USED WHEN THE CONTAINERS ARE FULL. THE 6 PARTICULAR CONTAINERS IN THIS DELIVERY WERE NOT EMBOSSED WITH A WARNING ABOUT THE HANDLES, BUT CURRENTLY THE CONTAINER MANUFACTURER EMBOSSES A WARNING ON THE TOP. WE HAVE INSTRUCTED OUR EMPLOYEE NOT TO USE THE HANDLES WHILE UNLOADING THESE CONTAINERS WHILE THEY ARE FULL. FURTHERMORE, WE WILL BE INCLUDING THIS INSTRUCTION IN THE NEXT COMPANY-WIDE MONTHLY SAFETY MEETING.    ATTACHMENT INCLUDED FROM THE CONTAINER MANUFACTURE WHICH INDICATES "MOLDED HAND HOLDS FOR EASY MANUAL HANDLING WHEN EMPTY".

column168: FLIGHT 167 ARRIVED IN BNA AND WHILE UNLOADING CARGO, IT WAS NOTICED THAT 2 BOXES OF A BIOLOGICAL SUBSTANCE, CATEGORY 8 SHIPMENT WAS LEAKING. THERE WERE ACTUALLY 2 DIFFERENT AIR WAYBILLS IN THE SHIPMENT AND THE TOTAL PIECE COUNT WAS 9 BOXES.   AWB 3288-7643 HAD 7 PCS (2 LEAKING),   AWB 3277-4136 HAD 2 PCS (1 BOX OPEN)  THESE SHIPMENTS WERE NOT PACKAGED PROPERLY PER 49 CFR 173.199, ALL PACKAGES ON THESE TWO AIR WAYBILLS WERE REMOVED FROM TRANSPORTATION AND THE NRC WAS NOTIFIED (REPORT #1052003). WE HELD SHIPMENT UNTIL WE COULD GET PICTURES SENT TO THE FAA. ONCE THAT WAS COMPLETED, AN EMPLOYEE FROM LABCORP PICKED UP THE PACKAGES IN ORDER TO PROPERLY PACKAGE THEM SO THEY COULD BE RE-OFFERED.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation.  Upon arrival at the 10-day transfer facility, driver conducted a thorough post trip inspection and noted free liquid on top of one of the totes.  The building was evacuated for approximately 1/2 hour. An in-house response team entered the trailer to investigate the situation. It was discovered that the cap closure on one of the totes was not closed properloy prior to shipment.  The spill was cleaned up by the response team.  The waste generated from the spill cleanup was containerized and will be managed appropriateoly by CHES.

column168: THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED METAL CASE SHIPMENT WAS NOTICED DUE TO A BURING SMELL AND STRONG ODOR. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS IN THIS METAL CASE WERE 2 BATTERIES, AND 12 AEROSOL CANS, ALONG WITH COUNTLESS OTHER THINGS. IT WAS BELIEVED THAT THE BATTERY HAD ARCHED BY TOUCHING THE METAL CASE WHILE IN TRANSIT. CHERICE McDANIEL OF THE IND/FAA WAS CONTACTED AT 8:45 ON 6-28-2013 TO ADVISE OF THE SHIPMENT FOR HER TO INVESTIGATE. IT WAS LATER DETERMINED BY MY DANGEROUS GOODS PERSONNEL IN IND THAT THE SHIPMENT WAS A DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE, (DOD), SHIPMENT SO I CONTACTED THE FAA AGAIN TO ADVISE. THE SHIPMENT WAS TO BE RELEASED AND MOVED TO THE CONSIGNEE PER FAA INSTRUCTIONS. THE DANGEROUS ITEMS WERE REMOVED AND THE REST OF THE SHIPMENT WAS TO BE RELEASED TO THE SHIPPER ON 7-22-13

column17: BETTER MANAGEMENT CORPORATION OF OHIO, INC.
column168: ON JUNE 3, 2013, OUR INDEPENDENT CONTRACTOR, HERMAN DOOLIN LOADED 43,040 POUNDS OF EAF DUST AT STEEL DYNAMICS, INC. ("SDI") IN BUTLER, IN AT APPROXIMATELY 6:00 P.M. WHILE LEAVING THE FACILITY, MR. DOOLIN WAS SPILLING, SPORADICALLY, THE DUST OUT OF THE BACK OF HIS TRAILER. A SDI EMPLOYEE, WHO WAS HEADING HOME FROM HIS SHIFT, NOTICED THE SPORADIC TRAIL AND INFORMED THE DRIVER. SDI CALLED GAVIN MCGAFFIN OF HORSEHEAD CORPORATION TO REPORT THE ISSUE. MR. MCGAFFIC IN TURNED CALLED OUR VP OF TRANSPORTATION, PAUL WILSON. LUCKILY, I WAS AT A BUSINESS DINNER WITH MR. WILSON IN NEWARK, NJ SO I WAS ABLE TO GET ON A CALL WITH MR. DOOLIN. MR. DOOLIN REPORTED THAT HE TOOK THE TRAILER TO EVANS TRUCK AND TRAILER IN BUTLER, IN BECAUSE THE WINDERS "WERE TOO SHORT" ON THE TRAILER SO THE GATE DID NOT COMPLETELY CLOSE LEAVING A SMALL CRACK, LESS THAN ONE INCH. THE DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS APPROXIMATELY TEN MINUTES WHILE DRIVING OF THE FACILITY ALONG HIS ROUTE OF TRAVEL ALONG COUNTY ROAD 59 AND STATE ROUTE 6 EAST.  BARRY SMITH, ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER OF SDI, TOOK OVER WITH THE CLEAN-UP. POWERCLEAN CLEANED THE SPILL AT THEIR SITE. ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION SERVICES, INC ("ERS") WERE CALLED TO HANDLE THE CLEAN-UP ALONG STATE ROUTE 6 AND THE SPOTS ALONG THE ROUTE, CLEAN-UP WAS COMPLETED BY ERS BY JUNE 4, 2013.  IT WAS DETERMINED BY EVANS TRUCK AND TRAILER AND MR. SMITH OF SDI, THAT THIS SPILL WAS DUE TO DRIVER ERROR. AFTER LINING HIS TRAILER WITH PLASTIC, AS REQUIRED, MR. DOOLIN LOADED THE TRAILER WITH THE DUST PRIOR TO TIGHTENING THE WINDERS ON THE TAILGATE. THIS CAUSES THE TRAILER TO BULGE AND WILL NOT ALLOW THE WINDERS TO CLOSE THE TAILGATE COMPLETELY. THE DRIVER IS TO TIGHTEN THE WINDERS AFTER LINING THE TRAILER AND BEFORE LOADING.
column169: A STEP WILL BE ADDED TO OUR PROCEDURES WITH REGARDS TO DUMP TRAILER OPERATIONS TO INCLUDE MAKING SURE THE WINDERS ON ALL DUMP TRAILERS ARE TIGHTENED AFTER LINING THE TRAILER AND PRIOR TO LOADING. THIS UPDATE WILL BE SENT TO ALL DRIVERS. ADDITIONAL TRAINING WIL LBE PROVIDED DURING OUR NEXT SAFETY MEETINGS AND THIS WILL BE INCLUDED IN OUR NEW DRIVER ORIENTATION.

column168: Driver overestimated the turn and struck the crash cushion barrels and concrete retaining wall with the left side of the tanker trailer. This caused the tractor and trailer to overturn on its left side and come to a rest on the off ramp. No other vehicles or persons were involved in this incident. Driver was not seriously injured. Because of the impact and overturn, methanol was slowly leaking out of the 3 inch wash out cap on top of trailer. Methanol was contained by Fire Hazmat Team and they and a company contracted private hazmat response team contained the methanol and transferred the remaining methanol to a safe container, cleaned up the spilled methanol from roadway and towing company removed the damaged tractor and trailer. Due to the nature of methanol, most of the released methanol evaporated shortly after the release.
column169: Revisions were made to company's Driver Safety Manual, to better reflect how drivers are to safely conduct themselves and report any future incidents. The driver that was involved in the incident was terminated. A detailed and lengthy safety meeting is scheduled this month, in which the company officials will go over this incident in great detail and discuss future improvements in safety procedures and safe driving. The reason for a slight delay in having this safety meeting is because the company wanted to have all details, costs, and reports from all agencies involved to better inform its personnel.

column168: ON 6/19/13 OUR TRACTOR/TRAILER WAS BEING TOWED BY A BULLDOZER AFTER BEING STRUCK IN THE MUD. UNITS WERE TRAVELING SOUTH ON COUNTY ROAD 484 ATTEMPTING TO TURN WEST ON COUNTY ROAD 488. THE ROADWAY CAVED IN DUE TO EXCESSIVE RAIN CAUSING OUR TRACTOR/TRAILER TO ROLL OVER ON ITS' PASSENGER SIDE AT APPROXIMATELY 7:00 P.M. NO CRUDE OIL WAS RELEASE DUE TO THE ROLLOVER. WHILE OFFLOADING THE TRAILER ONTO ANOTHER TRUCK A CONNECTION ON THE VENT LINE LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF CRUDE OIL ONTO THE RAINWATER IN THE BARDITCH. USING A DOZER WE DAMMED UP THE DITCH APPROXIMATELY 25 YARDS TO THE EAST OF THE CULVER AT THE INTERSECTION OF COUNTY ROADS 484 AND 488 STOPPING THE FLOW OF WATER AND OIL. THE TRACTOR/TRAILER WAS REMOVED FROM THE SIGHT AT APPROXIMATELY 3:00 A.M. ON 6/20/13. AT 7:30 A.M. ON 6/20/13 WE RETURNED TO THE SIGHT WITH A DOZER AND VACUUM TRUCK FROM DUNAGIN TRANSPORT. VACUUM TRUCK REMOVED ALL WATER AND OIL FROM BARDITCH. AFTER DRAINING THE DITCH THERE WAS A 3' BY 5' SECTION OF STAINED SOIL IN BOTTOM OF DITCH. STAINED AREA WAS WASHED WITH FRESHWATER AND OIL AND WATER WERE REMOVED FROM DITCH AGAIN. AT APPROXIMATELY 1:30P.M. ON 6/20/13 DITCH WAS EMPTY AND CLEAN. NO OIL RESIDUE REMAINED. DUNAGIN TRANSPORT HAULED 300 BBLS OF WATER TO THEIR DISPOSAL IN JONES COUNTY IN ORDER TO EMPTY DITCH OF WATER AND APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF CRUDE OIL. DOZER REPAIRED CORNER OF ROAD AT INTERSECTION SO THAT IT WAS DRIVABLE FOR THE PUBLIC.
column169: INSTRUCT DRIVERS TO NOT TRAVEL ON COUNTY ROADS 484 OR 488 DURING WET CONDITONS. ALSO INSTRUCT THEM TAT IF CAUGHT ON COUNTY ROAD 484 DURING A RAINSTORM THAT THEY SHOULD EXIT TO THE NORTH NOT THE SOUTH.

column168: THE DRIVER OF THE BOBTAIL WAS MAKING A SCHEDULED DELIVERY AT APPROXIMATELY 6:30 AM ON 06/24/13. WHEN THE DRIVER WAS MAKING HIS DELIVERY HE HEARD A NOISE AND WAS TOLD THAT SMOKE WAS COMING FROM UNDER THE TRUCK. ONCE THE DRIVER WAS AWARE OF THE LEAK HE TURNED THE TRUCK OFF AND HIT THE EMERGENCY SHUT OFF. AT THIS POINT THE RELEASE OF GAS DID NOT STOP. THE GAS WAS COMING FROM THE AREA OF THE PUMP. MANY ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO STOP THE LEAK OR TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT TO ANOTHER BULK TRUCK BUT ALL ATTEMPTS FAILED. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED AT APPROXIMATELY 6:00 PM ON 06/24/13. ONCE THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED THE DECISION WAS MADE TO EVACUATE THE SURROUNDING AREA. ONCE THE TANK HAD COMPLETELY LEAKED OUT THE TRUCK WAS DRIVEN BACK TO THE PLANT. THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS A BROKEN SEAL ON THE PUMP. NO PROPERTY DAMAGE OR PERSONAL INJURIES RESULTED FROM THE INCIDENT.
column169: THE LEAK FROM THE SEAL OF THE PUMP COULD NOT HAVE BEEN AVOIDED, BUT, THE DURATION OF THE INCIDENT COULD HAVE BEEN SHORTENED BY HAVING A BETTER UNDERSTANDING OF THE INTERNAL VALVE. ALTHOUGH AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT THE INTERNAL WAS DIFFICULT TO SEE DUE TO THE ICE CAUSED BY THE LEAK.

HOSE FROM PUMP POPPED OFF. NO HOLD DOWN STRAPS AVAILABLE ON TRUCK. FUEL WAS CLEANED UP USING FLOOR DRY, AND POLY BARRELS PURCHASED AT MR. STATES TRAILER. column42: GASOHOL GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: THE DRIVER HAD A LOAD OF GASOHOL TO WIGGS COUNTRY STORE IN OSKALOOSA. DRIVER HOOKED UP THE DROP HOSE FROM CARGO TANK TO UNDERGROUND STORAGE. SHORTLY AFTER STARTING THE TRANSFER OF PRODUCT THE 3 INCH HOSE SPLIT ALMOST HALF WAY AROUND ONE FOOT FROM THE CARGO TANK END. AS SOON AS THE DRIVER REALIZED THE SPILL WAS HAPPENING HE SHUT THE CARGO TANK OFF. THE SPILL LASTED FOR PART OF A MINUTE. FLOOR DRY WAS USED ON THE CEMENT TO ABSORB THE GASOHOL. THE OSKALOOS FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED TO CAPTURE THE PRODUCT AT THE STORM SEWER DISCHARGE SITE. THE DNR WAS CALLED AND RESPONDED. HYDRO-CLEAN FROM DES MOINES WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SITE TO FINISH THE CLEANUP IN THE CREEK. I WAS TOLD BY THE DNR THAT APPROXIMATELY ONE INCH OF RAIN FELL SHORTLY AFTER THE SPILL. THE QUANTITY OF THE SPILL WAS ESTIMATED AT 200 GALLONS. I WAS TOLD NEXT DAY THE UNDERGROUND TANK INVENTORY REPORT SHOWED THAT THE SPILL WAS 107 GALLONS.
column169: ACTIONS TAKEN: DISPOSED OF OLD HOSE REPLACED WITH A NEW ONE.

column168: AN ESTIMATED 300 GALLONS (ESTIMATED BY SAN ANGELO FIRE MARSHALL) WAS RELEASED ONTO PAVEMENT IN THE LA QUINTA PARKING LOT AND REMAINED ON PAVEMENT WHERE PRODUCT AND WATER WERE CONTAINED BY DIRT DAM PLACED AT THE 4400 BLOCK OF BLUE RIDGE TRAIL. SODA ASH WAS APPLIED TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID, ALTERING THE PH. NO WATER BODY OR STORM WATER DRAINAGES WERE IMPACTED OR THREATENED BY THIS PRODUCT.    THE FOLLOWING CONTINUES TO DESCRIBE CLEANING SOLUTIONS (PO BOX 3371 BRYAN, TX) RECOVERY EFFORTS THE DAY OF THE EVENT AFTER SAN ANGELO FD RELEASED THE SCENE. SAFETY OF WORKERS AND THE CONSTANT FLOW OF MOTEL EMPLOYEES AND GUEST WAS A PRIORITY WHILE CONTINUING TO FOCUS ON THE TASK AT HAND. THE REMAINING PRODUCT ON THE TRANSPORT WAS OFF-LOADED AND TRANSPORTED TO AN OFF-SITE FACILITY. WE USED FRESH WATER FLUSH ON SEGMENTS OF ABOURT 250 FT. FLUSHING THE IMPACTED AREA WITH FRESH WATER, STOPPING WATER WITH DIRT DAM, AND COLLECTING WATER WITH A VACUUM TRUCK. PRESSURE WASHERS WERE USED TO REMOVE THE SODA ASH FROM THE PAVEMENT AND ALLOWING IT TO BE CARRIED IN THE WATER. DIRT FROM DAMS WERE COLLECTED BY BACKHOE AND SHOVELS, PLACED ON PLASTIC TARPS AND SAMPLES OF DIRT WERE TAKEN TO A THIRD PARTY LAB. WE COVERED DIRT WITH PLASTIC AND SECURED THE AREA WITH ORANGE CONSTRUCTION FENCING.
column169: YES, WE WERE ABLE TO TAKE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE OF THE INCIDENT. WE HAVE ADDED A MECHANISM TO TAKE THE STRESS LOAD OFF THE FLANGE WHILE IN TRANSPORT. THE MECHANISM WILL SUPPORT THE DISCHARGE VALVE AT THE OF THE TANK TO PREVENT FURTHER INCIDENTS.

column168: Aqua Ammonia was being unloaded from cargo tank to water facility in a closed system using  pump and hose. The operation is a city water facility which is equipped with automatic electronic monitored valves and horn alarms on plumbing and valves. The driver/unload-er had just completed a walk around inspection and was preparing to shut pumps, valves to disconnect when the off loading hose he was next to twisted indicating back pressure. The driver unloading immediately closed supply. The off loading transfer hose split exactly where the the driver unload-er was standing, spraying the front of driver unload-er face and chest. Even with his personal protective equipment the spray caused soaking. The city employee immediately put the driver unload-er under the emergency shower and driver unload-er was taken to the hospital to evaluated by a doctor of skin, eyes and lungs.  The driver/unload-er was released the same day of event. During the event no alarms were activated by city monitors. The volume was less than two gallons, under RQ with no spill clean-up necessary. What spray discharged from the hose occurred from three to five seconds, which evaporated. The new hose that ruptured was placed in service previously on 04-24-2013.
column169: A hooded spash proof tyvex suit and fully hooded Powered air purifying respirator (PAPR)is now used with air supply from canister cartridges fastened to the backside of the driver/unload-er in lieu of a standard full face-shield cartridge respirator. A auxiliary bypass was installed on the unloading plumbing in case the primary malfunctions. column168: On June 28th, 2014 at 10:55 hours, personnel in the CSXT Selkirk Yard discovered NATX 310464, a loaded UN 1267, Petroleum Crude Oil tank car to have wetness down the side of the tank car, coming from around the manway. The car was isolated and the Shipper, DPTS Marketing, LLC, was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2014-06-28-00081. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, EP+S of Vermont the Glenmont Branch office was dispatched to the scene, upon inspection it was determined that manway cover swing bolts where over tightened, a release of product was seeping between swing bolts 3 + 4, this over torqueing crushed the gasket causing a release of product, further inspection swing bolt #3 was galled/cross threaded, swing bolt #4 was broken off at the top of the seal placement tang, the gasket was inspected and replaced, the manway nozzle was wipe down and the cover was re-secured and tool tightened.  Mr. Paul Ferguson, Rail Logistics Manager, was notified of the situation found and the corrective action taken, RESCAR has been notified to handle the replacement of the manway cover swing bolts.    This incident DID require a special move.    Cause Code: 200 (5 points) 202 (5 points) 206 (5 points) 209 (5 points)   NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0)  = 100
column169: Discussed AAR Pamphlet 34 with Mr. Ferguson, for proper loading and unloading procedures of General Service Tank Cars.

column168: THATCHER TRANSPORTATION'S DRIVER, (JAMES DAVIS) DELIVERED TWO TRAILERS TO THE JIM BRIDGER POWER PLANT IN POINT OF ROCKS, WY; A LEAD TRAILER OF FERRIC SULFATE, AND A PUP TRAILER OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE. WHEN HE CHECKED IN WITH SECURITY HE PROVIDED A TICKET TO PLANT SECURITY THAT INDICATED THAT HE HAD T-CHLOR (SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE) AND FERRIC CHLORIDE RATHER THAN FERRIC SULFATE. SECURITY PERSONNEL NOTIFIED THE CONTROL ROOM OF THE DELIVERY AND THE CONTROL ROOM NOTIFIED CLAYTON GREEN, TELLING HIM THAT HE HAD A CHEMICAL DELIVERY.    THATCHER'S DRIVER AND THE PLANT OPERATOR DECIDED TO UNLOAD THE PUP TRAILER OF T-CHLOR FIRST, AND THE OPERATOR TOOK THE DRIVER TO UNIT 4 WHERE HE UNLOADED THE TRAILER OF T-CHLOR. PRIOR TO UNLOADING THE T-CHLOR AT UNIT 4, THE DRIVER SHOWED THE OPERATOR THE BILL OF LADING FOR THE T-CHLOR, AND THEN HOOKED THE HOSE UP.    WHEN THE T-CHLOR TRANSFER WAS COMPLETE, THE DRIVER ASKED THE OPERATOR WHERE THE LEAD TRAILER WENT, THINKING THAT SECURITY HAD ALREADY INFORMED HIM THAT THE LEAD TRAILER CONTAINED FERRIC SULFATE. THE ONLY INFORMATION THE OPERATOR HAD RECEIVED, HOWEVER, WAS FROM THE CONTROL ROOM THAT HE HAD A CHEMICAL DELIVERY AND HE THOUGHT THAT BOTH TRAILERS WERE T-CHLOR. THE PLANT OPERATOR WAS NOT SHOWN THE BILL OF LADING FOR THE FERRIC SULFATE. THE OPERATOR TOOK THE DRIVER TO UNIT 1, A T-CHLOR TANK, AND THE DRIVER STARTED UNLOADING THE FERRIC SULFATE INTO IT. THE DRIVER HAD NOT DELIVERED CHEMICALS TO THE PLANT BEFORE AND WAS NOT FAMILIAR WITH THE LOCATIONS WHERE EACH CHEMICAL NEEDS TO BE UNLOADED. AFTER APPROXIMATELY FIVE MINUTES, THE CO-MINGLING OF T-CHLOR AND FERRIC SULFATE STARTED TO EMIT A GASEOUS VAPOR THAT AFFECTED BOTH THE DRIVER AND THE OPERATOR. BOTH WERE INITIALLY COUGHING AND HAVING BREATHING PROBLEMS.    BOTH THE TRUCK DRIVER AND PLANT OPERATOR WERE TRANSPORTED TO SWEETWATER MEMORIAL HOSPITAL BY THE PLANT EMTS AS A PRECAUTION. NEITHER CLAYTON GREEN NOR JAMES DAVIS WAS ADMITTED, AND AFTER APPROXIMATELY TWO OF OBSERVATION, BORH WERE RELEASED.   APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF THE MIXED CHEMICALS WERE SPILLED INTO THE CONCRETE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT STRUCTURE INSIDE THE T-CHLOR BUILDING FROM THE INCIDENT AND IT'S ALMOST IMPOSSIBLE TO DETERMINE HOW MUCH VAPOR WAS RELEASED.
column169: TO PREVENT MISCOMMUNICATION IN THE FUTURE, ON EVERY CHEMICAL DELIVERY AT JIM BRIDGER POWER PLANT, OPERATORS WILL MEET THE DRIVER AT SECURITY AND INSPECT ALL  BILLS OF LADING TO SEE WHICH PRODUCTS ARE BEING DELIVERED.    JIM BRIDGER POWER PLANT WILL ALSO PLACE A PLACARD ON EACH STORAGE TANK WITH THE UN IDENTIFICATION NUMBER. THE OPERATOR AND THE DRIVER WILL THEN COMPARE IT TO THE UN IDENTIFICATION NUMBER ON THE BILL OF LADING AND THE PLACARDS THAT ARE ACTUALLY ON THE TRAILER TO ENSURE THEY MATCH. IF THEY DON'T MATCH, THE DELIVERY WILL CEASE UNTIL THE DISCREPANCY IS RESOLVED.

column168: A TRACTOR AND TRAILER BEING DRIVEN BY A SAFEWAY TRANSPORTATION DRIVER FAILED TO NEGOTIATE A TIGHT CURVE AT THE INTERSECTION OF HWY 146 AND HIGHWAY 225. THE DRIVER STRUCK THE CURB, AND LOST CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE. THE TRUCK AND TRAILER ROLLED OVER THE SIDE WALL OF THE ELEVATED HIGHWAY, AND FELL APPROXIMATELY 30 FT TO THE GROUND BELOW.  EMERGENCY RESPONDERS ARRIVED AT THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT, MEDIVACTED BOTH THE DRIVER AND A TRAINER TO MEDICAL FACILITIES AND SECURED THE AREA. SINCE THE PRODUCT WAS FLAMMABLE GAS (PROPANE), THE POLICE DECIDED TO STOP TRAFFIC ON HIGHWAY 146 AND HIGHWAY 225. LOCAL PERSONNEL IN PLANTS WERE ADVISED TO STAY WHERE THEY WERE UNTIL AN ASSESSMENT COULD BE MADE OF THE SITUATION. IT WAS DECIDED BY LOCAL POLICE AND THE OFFICIALS THAT IT WOULD BE BEST TO FLARE OFF THE PRODUCT. THE PRODUCT WAS FLARED OFF OVER THE NEXT 24 HOURS. PLEASE NOTE THE STATEMENT OF MR. BOBBY CRAIN ATTACHED AS ATTACHEMENT #2. HIGHWAY 225 EAST WAS SHUTDOWN FOR APPROXIMATELY 27 HOURS AND TRAFFIC WAS REROUTED AS A PRECAUTION WHILE THE RESPONDERS FLARED THE PROPANE OFF.
